15 ensure any recommendations balance the protection of individual liberties with the interests
16 of businesses and government institutions.
17 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES:
18 (1) Creation of House study committee. There is created the House Study Committee
19 on Civil Rights Protections.
20 (2) Members and officers. The committee shall be composed of five members of the
21 House of Representatives to be appointed by the Speaker of the House of
22 Representatives. The Speaker shall designate a member of the committee as chairperson
23 of the committee.
24 (3) Powers and duties. The committee shall undertake a study of the conditions, needs,
25 issues, and problems mentioned above or related thereto and recommend any action or
26 legislation which the committee deems necessary or appropriate, including, but not
27 limited to, the following:
28 (A) Conducting a comprehensive review of Georgia's existing anti-discrimination laws
29 and identifying any gaps in protections;
30 (B) Analyzing data and research on discrimination in employment, housing, public
31 accommodations, and public services in Georgia;
32 (C) Reviewing civil rights laws from other states and federal civil rights statutes for
33 guidance on best practices;
34 (D) Assessing enforcement mechanisms, including, but not limited to, the role of state
35 agencies, private rights of action, and remedies available to victims of discrimination;
36 (E) Evaluating the impact of potential legislation on businesses, government entities,
37 and affected communities; and
38 (F) Making recommendations for legislation to address any identified deficiencies in
39 Georgia's civil rights protections.
